post_text:
Our Director of Elementary shares a special moment with students during distance learning.
#RepostPlus @awrinkleinwakanda
- - - - - -
On Wednesdays, I teach writing to third grade. Since it was Earth Day, the plan was to have the class write a paragraph about one thing they can do to take care of our planet. Before we began the assignment, I asked how they were and how many of them missed school. They all raised their hands. Right then I decided that because every day should be Earth Day, we could do that assignment another day. Instead, they talked and wrote about the things they missed about school. These were some of their responses. The first one made me cry because I also miss the sounds of school. Ok, bye😩😩

post_text:
Earlier this year our students learned about Jerusalem and about the Western Wall.

The Western Wall is 2000 years old. It is the remain from the temple in Jerusalem, the capitol of Israel.

If you had the chance to visit the Western Wall, you would probably see the custom of putting notes inside the wall’s cracks.
This custom is a cultural habit. The belief is to go to the Western Wall, write your wish on a note, put it between the cracks of the wall and to wait for it to come true.

Last week the Shinshiniyot visited the Western Wall and put the notes our students wrote in the wall’s cracks.

Students learned about Chilean food, animals and sports. They also provided a center in which students could color the Chilean flag.
5th graders did an outstanding job of leading by example while presenting their country to our kindergarten classes.

Students in 1st grade learned about the imfamous Nazca lines in Peru. These lines were created over a thousand years ago. Students were fascinated by the designs, so we created our own! We used sand, glue, and red and brown paint. Some of the designs include a house, a face painting, some cars, and human beings.
#selapcs #dccharterproud #dcpubliccharterschools #hebrewimmersion
